r supporting performances (Ann B. Davis's Schultzy in The Bob Cummings Show), guest appearances by Paul Lynde and Charles Nelson Reilly, or scripted dialogue and situations, industry processes of casting and production routinely esteemed a camp aesthetic that renders all gender expression queer. By charting this unexpected history, Miller offers new ways of exploring how supposedly repressive popular media incubated queer, genderqueer, and transgender representations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aGender identity on television. 0aGender nonconformity on television. 0aHomosexuality and televisionzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aSituation comedies (Television programs)zUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 0aTelevisionxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aTransgender people in popular culturezUnited States. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Television / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2019z978311069632540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478003397zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478003397423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781478003397.jpg  a978-3-11-069632-5  DUK eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles